You are reviewing this AI-generated component. Which checklist step catches the first bug?

```tsx
import { useState, useEffect, useRef } from "react";

const SearchBox = ({ onSearch }: { onSearch: (q: string) => void }) => {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");
  const [debouncedQuery, setDebouncedQuery] = useState("");

  useEffect(() => {
    const timer = setTimeout(() => {
      setDebouncedQuery(query);
    }, 300);
  }, [query]);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (debouncedQuery) onSearch(debouncedQuery);
  }, [debouncedQuery]);

  return <input value={query} onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)} />;
};
```

Which checklist step would catch the problem in this AI-generated code?

```tsx
const ProductList = ({ products }: { products: Product[] }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Products ({products.length})</h2>
      <ul>
        {products.map(product => (
          <li>
            <img src={product.image} />
            <span>{product.name}</span>
            <span>${product.price}</span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};
```

An AI generates a user settings form. You run the full checklist. Which steps flag issues?

```tsx
const [name, setName] = useState(user.name);
const [email, setEmail] = useState(user.email);
const [isChanged, setIsChanged] = useState(false);

useEffect(() => {
  setIsChanged(name !== user.name || email !== user.email);
}, [name, email]);

const handleSave = () => {
  updateUser({ name, email });
};

return (
  <form onSubmit={handleSave}>
    <input value={name} onChange={e => setName(e.target.value)} />
    <input value={email} onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)} />
    <div onClick={handleSave} className="btn">Save</div>
  </form>
);
```
